<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1975,2038]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1436,151,213]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="262" pageId="16" pageNumber="261">
This is the 
<typeStatus box="[273,321,1975,2001]" pageId="16" pageNumber="261">type</typeStatus>
species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys" authorityYear="1862" box="[445,571,1975,2001]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="16" pageNumber="261" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[445,571,1975,2001]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="261">Megalestes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only species that has an inner lateral tooth in the middle of the cerci (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1420,1444]" captionTargetBox="[160,1427,195,1385]" captionTargetId="figure-34@14.[151,1436,181,1396]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Caudal appendages of males (dorsal view). a) australis; b) irma, paratype; c) distans, from Yaan, Sichuan; d) distans from Dashahe, Guizhou; e) heros; f) omeiensis, paratype; g) kurahashii; h) major; i) haui; j) “palaceus”; k) micans, bd: basal disk; l) “chengi”; m) riccii; n) “maai”; o) “tuska,” from Damingshan, Guangxi; p) “tuska,” from Jinxiu, Guangxi. (Scale bar = 0.5 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407489/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="261">Fig. 3h</figureCitation>
). Its paraprocts are almost spherical, covered with dense setae, with an acute dorsal base tooth pointed directly 
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="262" type="description">
upwards (
<figureCitation box="[262,344,151,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1319,1343]" captionTargetBox="[168,1412,187,1286]" captionTargetId="figure-17@19.[163,1423,181,1295]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 6. Line drawing of male paraprocts (lateral view). a) australis; b) distans; c) gyalsey; d) kurahashii; e) major; f) haui; g) heros; h) omeiensis; i) micans; j) micans; k) riccii; l) irma." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4407497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4407497/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="262">Fig. 6e</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Asahina" authorityYear="1985" box="[364,564,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Synlestidae" genus="Megalestes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="17" pageNumber="262" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="major">
<emphasis box="[364,564,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="262">Megalestes major</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[753,813,151,177]" name="India" pageId="17" pageNumber="262">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[825,895,151,177]" name="Nepal" pageId="17" pageNumber="262">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1037,151,177]" name="Bhutan" pageId="17" pageNumber="262">Bhutan</collectingCountry>
, and it only occurs on the west side of the Himalayas.
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
